  "shmL1S1Body": "Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM) is a type of periodic motion where the restoring force is directly proportional to the displacement from equilibrium. Think of a mass on a spring — when you pull it and let go, it bounces back and forth.",
  "shmL1S2Title": "Key Characteristics",
  "shmL1S2Body": "SHM has three key properties: (1) The motion repeats at regular intervals (periodic), (2) The acceleration is always directed toward the equilibrium position, (3) The acceleration is proportional to the displacement.",
  "shmL1S3Title": "Restoring Force",
  "shmL1S3Body": "The restoring force is what pulls the object back toward equilibrium. For a spring, this is given by Hooke's Law:",
  "shmL1S3Formula": "F = -kx",
  "shmL1S4Title": "Amplitude & Equilibrium",
  "shmL1S4Body": "The amplitude (A) is the maximum displacement from equilibrium. The equilibrium position is where the net force on the object is zero. The object oscillates between +A and -A.",
  "shmLesson2Title": "Period & Frequency",
  "shmLesson2Subtitle": "Timing the Oscillations",
  "shmL2S1Title": "What is Period?",
  "shmL2S1Body": "The period (T) is the time taken for one complete oscillation. For example, if a pendulum swings back and forth in 2 seconds, its period is 2 s.",
  "shmL2S2Title": "Period of a Spring",
  "shmL2S2Body": "The period of a mass-spring system depends only on the mass (m) and the spring constant (k):",
  "shmL2S2Formula": "T = 2π √(m/k)",
  "shmL2S3Title": "What is Frequency?",
  "shmL2S3Body": "Frequency (f) is the number of oscillations per second. It is the reciprocal of the period: f = 1/T. The unit of frequency is the Hertz (Hz).",
  "shmL2S4Title": "Angular Frequency",
  "shmL2S4Body": "Angular frequency (ω) relates to the period and frequency through:",
  "shmL2S4Formula": "ω = 2πf = 2π/T",
  "shmLesson3Title": "Energy in SHM",
  "shmLesson3Subtitle": "The Conservation of Energy",
  "shmL3S1Title": "Forms of Energy",
  "shmL3S1Body": "In SHM, energy constantly transforms between kinetic energy (KE) and potential energy (PE). At equilibrium, KE is maximum and PE is zero. At the amplitude endpoints, KE is zero and PE is maximum.",
  "shmL3S2Title": "Total Mechanical Energy",
  "shmL3S2Body": "The total mechanical energy in SHM remains constant (ignoring friction). For a spring-mass system:",
  "shmL3S2Formula": "E = ½kA²",
  "shmL3S3Title": "Energy at Any Point",
  "shmL3S3Body": "At any displacement x from equilibrium: KE = ½k(A² − x²) and PE = ½kx². The sum KE + PE = ½kA² is always constant.",
  "shmL3S4Title": "Velocity in SHM",
  "shmL3S4Body": "The velocity of the oscillating object at any displacement x is given by:",
  "shmL3S4Formula": "v = ±ω √(A² − x²)",
  "shmLesson4Title": "Real-World SHM",
  "shmLesson4Subtitle": "SHM in Everyday Life",
  "shmL4S1Title": "Pendulums",
  "shmL4S1Body": "A simple pendulum approximates SHM for small angles (less than 15°). The period depends only on the length (L) and gravity (g): T = 2π√(L/g). This is why pendulum clocks work!",
  "shmL4S2Title": "Waves & Sound",
  "shmL4S2Body": "Sound waves are longitudinal waves where air molecules oscillate back and forth in SHM. Musical instruments like tuning forks and guitar strings also vibrate in SHM.",
  "shmL4S3Title": "Molecular Vibrations",
  "shmL4S3Body": "At the atomic level, atoms in a molecule vibrate about their equilibrium positions in SHM. This is why solids have thermal energy — atoms are constantly oscillating.",
  "shmL4S4Title": "Engineering & Bridges",
  "shmL4S4Body": "Engineers must account for SHM when designing buildings and bridges. The Tacoma Narrows Bridge collapse in 1940 is a famous example of resonance — when an external force matches the natural frequency of a structure.",
  "shmQ1Question": "What is the restoring force in SHM proportional to?",
  "shmQ1Options": "[\"Velocity\",\"Displacement\",\"Time\",\"Mass\"]",
  "shmQ1CorrectIndex": "1",
  "shmQ1Explanation": "In SHM, the restoring force is directly proportional to the displacement from equilibrium (F = -kx).",
  "shmQ2Question": "What is the period of a mass-spring system with m = 4 kg and k = 100 N/m? (Assume π ≈ 3.14)",
  "shmQ2Options": "[\"0.63 s\",\"1.26 s\",\"2.51 s\",\"0.40 s\"]",
  "shmQ2CorrectIndex": "1",
  "shmQ2Explanation": "T = 2π√(m/k) = 2π√(4/100) = 2π × 0.2 = 1.26 seconds.",
  "shmQ3Question": "At which point in SHM is kinetic energy maximum?",
  "shmQ3Options": "[\"At the amplitude\",\"At equilibrium\",\"At the midpoint\",\"Kinetic energy is constant\"]",
  "shmQ3CorrectIndex": "1",
  "shmQ3Explanation": "Kinetic energy is maximum at the equilibrium position, where velocity is highest. At the endpoints, all energy is potential.",
  "shmQ4Question": "What happens to the period of a pendulum if the length is quadrupled?",
  "shmQ4Options": "[\"It doubles\",\"It halves\",\"It quadruples\",\"It stays the same\"]",
  "shmQ4CorrectIndex": "0",
  "shmQ4Explanation": "T ∝ √L, so if L increases by 4×, T increases by √4 = 2×.",
  "shmQ5Question": "The total mechanical energy in SHM is proportional to:",
  "shmQ5Options": "[\"The amplitude\",\"The square of the amplitude\",\"The mass\",\"The spring constant\"]",
  "shmQ5CorrectIndex": "1",
  "shmQ5Explanation": "Total energy E = ½kA², so it is proportional to the square of the amplitude (A²).",
